nal Climate Change Strategy identifies important lines of action, one of them being natural resource management (water resources, forests and biodiversity). In the Dominican Republic, the strategic areas mentioned for adaptation and mitigation of climate change are biodiversity, forests and coastal and marine resources. Among the measures that they propose are sustainable forest management programmes, re- forestation and afforestation. It also indicates that biological diversity and climate change must be considered with a holistic vision in order to combat desertification and soil degradation, and promote activities for conservation and sustainable use of biological diversity.87 Lastly, the countries are signatories to the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD), which means each country accepts responsi- bility for devising their respective national reports, and implementing the actions called for by the Conference of Parties. 85 All of these legislations are designed, regulated and applied by the ministries for natural resources of each country. 86 Idem 45 87 Secretaria de Estado de Medio Ambiente y Recursos Naturales. 2008. Lineamientos para una estrategia nacional de cambio clim\u00e1tico. Santo Domingo, Rep\u00fablica Dominicana. 32 The following table summarises the progress according to the Fifth National Report by country: Table 8. CBD. Fifth National Report. Achievements and progress88 Country CBD. Fifth National Report. Achievements and progress Mexico General Wildlife Law General Law of Sustainable Rural Development Sustainable Forest Development law Biosafety of Genetically Modified Organisms Law Sustainable Fisheries and Aquaculture Law Strategy for the Conservation and Management of Shorebirds and Their Habitat National Strategy on Invasive Species in Mexico, Prevention, Control and Eradication Climate Change Strategy for Protected Areas National Strategy for Conservation and Sustainable Development of the Mexican Insular Territory Mexican Strategy f